    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>More to Say on 'Pursuit of Less'</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alex Ryley letter on September 3 article notes those who have decided to simplify their lives live in some of trendiest New York neighborhoods (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The seekers of the simple life that you profiled share more than ''a dedication to voluntary simplicity.'' They also live in some of the trendiest neighborhoods in New York, where everything, from rent to groceries to dry cleaning, is significantly more expensive than it is elsewhere in the city.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The seekers of the simple life that you profiled share more than ''a dedication to voluntary simplicity.'' They also live in some of the trendiest neighborhoods in New York, where everything, from rent to groceries to dry cleaning, is significantly more expensive than it is elsewhere in the city.</p>
        <p>They may have stopped buying luxury items and otherwise simplified their lifestyles, but their choice to pay top dollar for a fashionable address belies their claims of asceticism.</p>
        <p>ALEX RYLEY  Woodside, Queens</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
